{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569388"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22101"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22101"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.1,0.21,0.13,0.55]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15062"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106932"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15062"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22101"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89418"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43757"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106932"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of progressive breathlessness with exercise and a persistent dry cough. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has been vaping nicotine-containing e-cigarettes daily for the past eight years, using approximately two pods per day. She works as a graphic designer in an office environment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with a pulse rate of 82/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals mild expiratory wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpirometry is performed with the following results:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Ctable\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003EParameter\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EPre-bronchodilator\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EPost-bronchodilator\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EPredicted\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EFEV1 (L)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E2.10 (65%)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E2.30 (71%)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E3.24\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EFVC (L)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E3.20 (82%)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E3.35 (86%)\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E3.90\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EFEV1/FVC\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E0.66\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E0.69\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E0.83\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate interpretation of these spirometry results?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal spirometry","Restrictive lung disease","Mixed obstructive and restrictive pattern","Reversible airway obstruction consistent with asthma","Fixed airflow limitation consistent with COPD"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s spirometry results demonstrate \u003Cstrong\u003Efixed airflow limitation consistent with COPD\u003C/strong\u003E. The key diagnostic criterion for COPD is a post-bronchodilator FEV1/FVC ratio \u0026lt;0.7, which this patient has (0.69). The diagnosis requires compatible clinical features (dyspnoea, chronic cough) combined with spirometric evidence of persistent airflow limitation. The patient\u0027s post-bronchodilator FEV1 is 71% of predicted, classifying this as mild COPD (FEV\u003Csub\u003E1\u003C/sub\u003E \u2248 60-80% predicted is mild, FEV\u003Csub\u003E1\u003C/sub\u003E \u2248 40-59% predicted is moderate and FEV\u003Csub\u003E1\u003C/sub\u003E \u0026lt; 40% predicted is severe).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal spirometry\u003C/strong\u003E would show an FEV1/FVC ratio \u22650.7 and both FEV1 and FVC \u226580% predicted. This patient\u0027s FEV1/FVC ratio of 0.69 clearly indicates airflow obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERestrictive lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E presents with reduced FVC (\u0026lt;80% predicted) but a normal or increased FEV1/FVC ratio, as both volumes are proportionally reduced. This patient shows an obstructive pattern with reduced FEV1/FVC ratio and preserved FVC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReversible airway obstruction consistent with asthma\u003C/strong\u003E requires significant bronchodilator response (\u226512% and \u2265200 mL improvement in FEV1) with normalisation of the FEV1/FVC ratio. While this patient shows some response (10% improvement), the FEV1/FVC ratio remains \u0026lt;0.7, indicating fixed obstruction rather than asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed obstructive and restrictive pattern\u003C/strong\u003E would show both a reduced FEV1/FVC ratio and an FVC \u0026lt;80% predicted. This patient\u0027s FVC is within normal limits (86% predicted post-bronchodilator), excluding a restrictive component.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of COPD at age 32 is highly unusual and requires careful evaluation. According to COPD-X guidelines, COPD in patients under 45 years warrants investigation for alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency, which can cause early-onset emphysema. This patient should have alpha-1 antitrypsin levels checked and requires referral to a respiratory specialist for comprehensive assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s eight-year history of daily vaping represents a significant risk factor. E-cigarettes containing nicotine cause airway inflammation, oxidative stress, and impaired mucociliary clearance. Studies have shown that vaping can lead to small airway dysfunction and increased susceptibility to respiratory infections. The COPD-X guidelines acknowledge e-cigarettes as an emerging risk factor for respiratory disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement should follow the COPD-X stepwise approach, beginning with smoking cessation support (including vaping cessation), pulmonary rehabilitation, and appropriate pharmacotherapy. Given the mild severity, initial treatment would typically involve short-acting bronchodilators as needed. The patient should receive influenza, COVID-19 and pneumococcal vaccinations as per guidelines. Long-term monitoring with annual spirometry is recommended to assess disease progression, particularly important in this young patient. The specialist assessment will help exclude other diagnoses, optimise management, and screen for genetic causes of early-onset COPD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["COPD in young adults requires investigation for alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency and referral to a respiratory specialist.","Vaping is an emerging risk factor for early-onset COPD, with nicotine-containing e-cigarettes causing airway inflammation and oxidative stress.","Post-bronchodilator spirometry showing FEV1/FVC \u003C0.7 confirms COPD diagnosis, with severity graded by FEV1 percentage of predicted."],"references":["Lung Foundation Australia. COPD\u2011X Plan Handbook, Version 1. Melbourne: Lung Foundation Australia; 2024 Aug. Available from: https://lungfoundation.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/COPD-X_Handbook_Version1.pdf","National Asthma Council Australia. Spirometry Handbook \u2013 2023 (Colour). Carlton South, VIC: National Asthma Council Australia; 2023. Available from: https://files.nationalasthma.org.au/resources/Spirometry-Handbook-2023-Colour.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89418"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22101"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89418"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T09:25:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T09:27:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15062"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106932"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}